    coreTraits: ['Analytical', 'Meticulous', 'Helpful', 'Practical', 'Modest', 'Critical'],
    strengths: ['Extraordinary attention to detail', 'Problem-solving intelligence', 'Work ethic', 'Reliability', 'Genuine helpfulness'],
    challenges: ['Perfectionism that prevents starting', 'Excessive criticism of self and others', 'Anxiety', 'Overthinking'],
    inLove: "Virgo in love is an act of service — they show up practically, remember small things, notice what their partner needs before it is expressed, and quietly make life run more smoothly. They do not lead with grand romantic gestures; they lead with competence and care. The challenge: their critical faculties, which make them so effective in everything else, can become harsh in relationships — nitpicking what they should be accepting. Best matched with Taurus and Capricorn (earth signs who value the same attention to quality), and Cancer and Scorpio who appreciate depth.",
    atWork: "Virgo is the professional everyone eventually realizes they could not function without. They spot the error, fix the problem, and improve the system — usually without being asked and definitely without making a fuss about it. Best career fits: medicine, research, editing, accounting, data analysis, nutrition, veterinary science, engineering, quality control, and any field where precision is the difference between good and excellent.",
    mythology: "Virgo is associated with Demeter (Roman: Ceres) — goddess of the harvest, grain, and fertile earth. Some traditions associate Virgo with Persephone, Demeter's daughter, whose abduction by Hades created the seasons: Demeter's grief made the earth barren in winter; her daughter's return brought spring. Others connect Virgo to Astraea, goddess of justice and innocence, the last immortal to leave Earth at the end of the Golden Age. All three figures share Virgo's qualities: care for the natural world, service to others, and an exacting standard of purity. [Source: Grimal, P. (1951). The Dictionary of Classical Mythology. Blackwell.]",
    history: "In Babylonian astronomy, the constellation Virgo was associated with the goddess Shala (later Ishtar/Inanna) — the great goddess of fertility and grain. The heliacal rising of Virgo marked the wheat harvest in ancient Mesopotamia, which is why the association with agriculture and careful practical work has been consistent across cultures for over 3,000 years. [Source: Sachs, A., 1952. Babylonian Horoscopes. Journal of Cuneiform Studies.]",
    fullDescription: "The thing about Virgo is that they are almost never the loudest person in the room — but they are almost always the most essential. They are the ones who actually read the fine print, who remember the detail everyone else glossed over, who will quietly fix something three days before it would have become an emergency. Ruled by Mercury, Virgo has the analytical mind of an air sign in an earth body — all that mental precision applied to the tangible, the practical, the fixable. Beyoncé's career is the ultimate argument for Virgo. She does not release work until it is ready. When she does perform, every element — choreography, lighting, production, vocal performance — is executed at a level of deliberate excellence that makes other artists look spontaneous by comparison. This is not perfectionism in the anxious sense (though that version of Virgo also exists). It is craftsmanship: the belief that the gap between good and excellent is worth closing. Mother Teresa exemplifies Virgo's other great quality: service as a daily, concrete, unglamorous practice. Not service as an idea, but service as showing up in person, attending to specific individual needs, doing the actual work that nobody photographs. The central Virgo challenge is turning the analytical lens inward with the same compassion they show outward. The inner critic that makes Virgo so effective in their craft can become a voice that makes them feel they are never enough. The most evolved Virgos — and there are many — have learned to apply their famous discernment to that inner critic too: to notice it, question it, and choose not to obey it.",
