    inLove: "Libra is perhaps the most partnership-oriented sign in the zodiac — they genuinely come alive in a committed relationship in a way that other signs do not. They are romantic, attentive, and naturally inclined toward compromise. The challenge: they can suppress their own needs so thoroughly in service of keeping the peace that resentment builds invisibly, then erupts unexpectedly. They also struggle to leave relationships that have clearly run their course because they hate causing pain. Best matched with Gemini and Aquarius (air signs who share their values), and Leo and Sagittarius who appreciate Libra's grace.",
    atWork: "Libra is the natural diplomat, mediator, and creative collaborator of the workplace. They see all sides of every argument, which makes them invaluable in negotiations — and frustrating to people who need immediate decisions. Best career fits: law, diplomacy, design, fashion, art curation, public relations, marriage counseling, architecture, human resources, and any role requiring both aesthetic judgment and interpersonal skill.",
    mythology: "Libra, uniquely among the zodiac signs, is not represented by an animal or mythological figure but by an object — the Scales. In ancient Greek and Roman mythology, the scales were the instrument of Themis (Justice) and her daughter Dike (Astraea) — the goddesses responsible for maintaining divine law and moral order. In Egyptian mythology, the scales appear in the ceremony of psychostasia: the weighing of the dead soul's heart against the feather of Ma'at (truth and justice). If the heart balanced perfectly, the soul passed to paradise. The scales are therefore one of the most enduring symbols of fairness, balance, and ethical judgment in human history. [Source: Grimal, P. (1951). The Dictionary of Classical Mythology. Blackwell.]",
    history: "Libra is the only sign in the zodiac represented by an inanimate object, which has fascinated astrologers since ancient times. The Babylonians originally called this constellation the Claws (of the Scorpion), but the Romans reinterpreted it as the Scales of Astraea — the last goddess to abandon Earth. The Romans elevated Libra's importance significantly, associating it with Venus and the values of civilization: beauty, law, and harmonious society. [Source: Campion, N., 2009. A History of Western Astrology. Continuum.]",
    fullDescription: "Libra has the reputation of being indecisive, and this is partly true — but it misses the deeper reason. Libra is not indecisive because they cannot think clearly. They are indecisive because they can see too clearly: every option's merits and flaws, every person's perspective, every consequence that might ripple from a choice. To a sign wired for balance and fairness, making a final decision always feels like a small injustice to the alternatives. Ruled by Venus, Libra has a deep aesthetic intelligence — they notice when something is off in a room, in a relationship, in a piece of music, long before they can articulate why. This sensitivity to harmony and imbalance makes them extraordinary designers, diplomats, and partners. Serena Williams demonstrates that Libra is not soft — she has won 23 Grand Slam titles through iron discipline and fierce competitiveness. But she has also used her platform consistently to advocate for equal pay, representation, and fairness in her sport. The scales tip both ways: Libra can be the most charming person in the room or the most difficult to pin down. The central Libra evolution is learning that their own needs and opinions deserve to be on the scales too — that genuine fairness includes fairness to themselves. The Libra who learns this stops being diplomatically dishonest (saying yes when they mean no, agreeing when they disagree) and becomes something rarer: genuinely fair.",
