    inLove: "Scorpio in love is total and intense — they do not do casual. Once they have decided someone matters, they give completely, and they expect the same in return. Trust is everything; betrayal is something they may never fully forgive. Jealousy is Scorpio's great relationship challenge — it comes from depth of feeling, but it can poison what it is trying to protect. Best matched with Cancer and Pisces (fellow water signs who understand the emotional depth), and Taurus and Capricorn who can withstand the Scorpio intensity.",
    atWork: "Scorpio excels in work that requires penetrating through surface appearances to find hidden truth. They are the researchers, investigators, therapists, and strategists of the zodiac — effective in any field that rewards psychological depth and strategic thinking. Best career fits: psychology, medicine, research, law enforcement, intelligence, finance, surgery, investigative journalism, and any role requiring absolute focus.",
    mythology: "Scorpio's mythology centers on the battle between Scorpius and Orion — the great hunter who boasted he would kill every animal on Earth. Gaia (or Artemis, in some versions) sent the Scorpion to protect the animals. The scorpion killed Orion with a single sting. Both were placed in the sky but on opposite sides — Scorpius in winter, Orion in summer — so they would never face each other again. The myth captures Scorpio's nature perfectly: quiet power, the ability to defeat something seemingly much larger, and the permanent mark left on the world by their actions. [Source: Grimal, P. (1951). The Dictionary of Classical Mythology. Blackwell.]",
    history: "Scorpio is one of the oldest recognized constellations, with references in Babylonian astronomical texts dating to at least 1200 BCE. The Babylonians called it GIR.TAB (the Scorpion), associated it with Ishhara, the goddess of love and war, and recognized it as a major marker in the sky. Pluto, assigned as Scorpio's co-ruler in modern astrology, was discovered in 1930 — adding depth and transformation to the sign's traditional Mars associations. [Source: Campion, N., 2009. A History of Western Astrology. Continuum.]",
    fullDescription: "Scorpio has the most unfair reputation in the zodiac. Yes, they can be intense. Yes, they have a long memory and a complex relationship with power. But what gets left out is that Scorpio is also the sign most capable of transformation — of genuine, bone-deep change that reshapes who they are. Ruled by Pluto (transformation, death, rebirth) and Mars (action, desire), Scorpio operates in extremes. They are not interested in the surface of anything. When they love, they want the whole truth of a person — the darkness included. When they investigate, they go until they find what is actually there, not what was meant to be found. Leonardo DiCaprio has spent his career inhabiting characters in psychological extremity — the obsessive Jay Gatsby, the trauma-scarred frontiersman of The Revenant, the morally dissolving Jordan Belfort — precisely because Scorpio instinctively understands that it is in the dark places where the most interesting and true things live. Virat Kohli's famous intensity — the burning refusal to lose, the sheer will that has won him records across formats — is the Scorpio will operating in sport: unstoppable, uncompromising, and slightly terrifying to opponents. The Scorpio growth edge is trust. Not the naive kind — Scorpio is correct that the world is complex and people's motives are mixed. But the evolved Scorpio learns to be vulnerably present enough to let real connection form, rather than testing everything until it breaks. Their greatest transformation, ultimately, is of themselves.",
