    mythology: "Capricorn's symbol — the Sea Goat, a creature with the body of a goat and the tail of a fish — is one of the most ancient in the zodiac. In Sumerian mythology, it represented the god Enki (Sumerian) or Ea (Akkadian), the god of wisdom, water, and creation who was often depicted as a goat-fish. In Greek mythology, Capricorn is associated with the goat-god Pan, who jumped into the Nile River to escape the monster Typhon, transforming his lower half into a fish tail. Zeus immortalized the transformation in the stars. The Sea Goat captures something essential about Capricorn: a creature that can navigate both the most rugged terrain (the mountain goat) and the depths of water (the fish tail). [Source: Grimal, P. (1951). The Dictionary of Classical Mythology. Blackwell.]",
    history: "Capricorn is one of the most ancient recognized constellations, documented in Babylonian records from the Bronze Age. The Babylonians called it SUHUR.MÁŠ, the goat-fish, and associated it with the winter solstice. In ancient Mesopotamian calendars, the winter solstice period was associated with death, darkness, and the need for patience and endurance before the return of light — themes that map directly onto Capricorn's Saturn-ruled qualities. [Source: Campion, N., 2009. A History of Western Astrology. Continuum.]",
    fullDescription: "Capricorn is the sign of the long game, and they play it better than almost anyone. Ruled by Saturn — the planet of time, structure, discipline, and hard-won wisdom — Capricorn understands something that the flashier signs tend to miss: that most truly worthwhile things cannot be rushed. They are built slowly, layer by layer, through sustained effort and the willingness to delay gratification in service of something larger. LeBron James has managed his career with a Capricorn's deliberate strategy: choosing his teams, managing his business empire, and pacing his physical investment so that his performance arc has been consistently extraordinary across two decades rather than briefly brilliant. Michelle Obama took three career pivots — corporate lawyer, nonprofit executive, First Lady, author — each one more influential than the last, each chosen with characteristic Capricorn purpose. The Sea Goat symbol is telling. Capricorn can climb the mountain — sustained ambition, strategic patience, the ability to operate in difficult terrain — but also the depths (the fish tail), suggesting that there is more going on beneath the Capricorn surface than the composed exterior reveals. The central Capricorn challenge is remembering that achievement is not identity. The Capricorn who has equated their worth with their professional accomplishments is the one who burns out, or who reaches the summit and finds it empty. The evolved Capricorn — and there are many, because Capricorn tends to do the inner work with the same discipline they bring to everything else — discovers that the real climb was never up the mountain at all.",
